because it really would have saved a lot of time.

30
00:01:10,904 --> 00:01:13,065
Speaking of saving time, this talk is jam-packed,

31
00:01:13,165 --> 00:01:14,166
so this overview is quick.

32
00:01:14,987 --> 00:01:17,269
Part one, guiding players with block mesh layouts with me,

33
00:01:17,829 --> 00:01:20,191
and part two, Robert will be talking about level lighting.

34
00:01:20,531 --> 00:01:20,831
Let's go.

35
00:01:21,832 --> 00:01:23,854
First up, let's get all on the same page.

36
00:01:24,754 --> 00:01:25,955
What the heck is block mesh?

37
00:01:27,609 --> 00:01:31,412
Well, at Naughty Dog, we call levels built with simple geometry and textures block mesh.

38
00:01:31,973 --> 00:01:34,815
Unfortunately, our industry hasn't arrived at a single term at this yet.

39
00:01:35,235 --> 00:01:38,478
It's actually, they also call it gray box and white box and all kinds of things.

40
00:01:39,279 --> 00:01:42,182
Mostly, I prefer block mesh because it includes color and lighting,

41
00:01:42,582 --> 00:01:46,105
which are very important when playtesting layouts since they help guide players.

42
00:01:47,062 --> 00:01:49,624
Also, handing off colored block meshes to your artists

43
00:01:49,784 --> 00:01:51,125
make it a lot easier to communicate

44
00:01:51,265 --> 00:01:53,847
the kinds of textures and colors you had in mind.

45
00:01:54,507 --> 00:01:56,028
Green floor, it's probably grass.

46
00:01:56,268 --> 00:01:57,309
Brown, it's probably dirt.

47
00:01:58,810 --> 00:02:01,371
Now let's look at a common level design process

48
00:02:01,412 --> 00:02:02,172
at a game studio.

49
00:02:02,872 --> 00:02:04,453
First, you need to establish the context

50
00:02:04,493 --> 00:02:05,514
and constraints of your level.

51
00:02:06,415 --> 00:02:08,116
This includes things like the environment type,

52
00:02:08,356 --> 00:02:10,277
the time of day, location in the story,

53
00:02:10,457 --> 00:02:13,079
available character abilities, enemy types, all that stuff.

54
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:15,641
You should decide on the gameplay and narrative beats,

55
00:02:15,701 --> 00:02:15,841
too.

56
00:02:17,181 --> 00:02:18,561
Once you have your requirements in Beats,

57
00:02:19,001 --> 00:02:21,942
dive right into building a rough version of the entire level

58
00:02:22,242 --> 00:02:24,383
so that you can get a sense of pacing and scale.

59
00:02:25,123 --> 00:02:27,203
Be sure to stub in those game plan narrative beats, too.

60
00:02:28,544 --> 00:02:30,184
Get something playable quickly, and then watch

61
00:02:30,244 --> 00:02:30,984
other people play it.

62
00:02:31,404 --> 00:02:33,105
There's no need for a formal play test or anything.

63
00:02:33,125 --> 00:02:35,885
You can just grab anybody, because the feedback

64
00:02:35,905 --> 00:02:37,766
that you get from them is going to change a block mesh.

65
00:02:38,506 --> 00:02:41,667
Repeat this iteration loop until you basically run out of time.

66
00:02:42,627 --> 00:02:44,627
And once you run out of time, your layout's locked,

67
00:02:44,767 --> 00:02:46,068
and you hand it off to the rest of the team

68
00:02:46,108 --> 00:02:46,948
to make it look amazing.

69
00:02:47,573 --> 00:02:48,673
But your job isn't done yet.

70
00:02:49,114 --> 00:02:51,815
Your task at this stage is to ensure that your design goals

71
00:02:52,035 --> 00:02:53,196
mesh with their artistic goals.

72
00:02:53,756 --> 00:02:55,878
So keep playtesting and work with your artists

73
00:02:55,918 --> 00:02:58,059
to ensure that it still plays great with the real art.

74
00:02:58,899 --> 00:03:00,160
Now, it's worth noting that every studio

75
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:01,041
has a different process.

76
00:03:01,521 --> 00:03:03,522
But this core iteration loop is universal.

77
00:03:04,703 --> 00:03:06,104
So now let's get to the block mesh tips.

78
00:03:06,704 --> 00:03:08,525
Now, our game director Kurt told me

79
00:03:08,565 --> 00:03:10,086
that tips wasn't a strong enough word

80
00:03:10,106 --> 00:03:11,087
for how important these are.

81
00:03:11,107 --> 00:03:14,128
So I'm going to rename them now to guidance principles.

82
00:03:15,683 --> 00:03:17,485
So first up, we have affordance.

83
00:03:19,166 --> 00:03:20,967
One of the most powerful ways to guide players

84
00:03:21,047 --> 00:03:23,528
is by using affordances, which are properties of an object

85
00:03:23,808 --> 00:03:26,290
that define its possible uses and make clear

86
00:03:26,330 --> 00:03:27,110
how it should be used.

87
00:03:28,211 --> 00:03:29,852
A classic example is a door handle.

88
00:03:30,492 --> 00:03:32,434
Just by looking at a push bar or a pull handle,

89
00:03:32,734 --> 00:03:34,715
you intuit whether or not to push or pull the door

90
00:03:34,855 --> 00:03:35,435
as you approach.

91
00:03:36,556 --> 00:03:37,577
Ladders afford climbing.

92
00:03:39,178 --> 00:03:40,338
Edges also afford climbing.

93
00:03:41,913 --> 00:03:45,815
Ramps afford jumping off or smashing through a vent in Wolfenstein 2.

94
00:03:46,635 --> 00:03:49,957
Affordances depend on your game rules because that's what they're communicating to the player.

95
00:03:51,177 --> 00:03:55,079
So for our game designers, affordance is a great way to communicate to the player

96
00:03:55,379 --> 00:03:57,600
what they can interact with or where they can go.

97
00:03:58,300 --> 00:04:01,782
Players will learn what is interactive and it will attract them towards these affordances.

98
00:04:03,042 --> 00:04:05,543
Consistent Color and Shape establish a trust contract

99
00:04:05,844 --> 00:04:08,425
with players who use these to learn your game rules.

100
00:04:09,869 --> 00:04:12,830
You should ensure that all of your affordances work consistently throughout the game,

101
00:04:12,951 --> 00:04:15,972
or it breaks that trust contract, which will cause player frustration.

102
00:04:17,553 --> 00:04:20,354
You should also include affordances in your block mesh phase.

103
00:04:20,834 --> 00:04:22,455
It'll help guide players where you want them to go.

104
00:04:22,475 --> 00:04:23,856
So let's see what it looks like.

105
00:04:26,537 --> 00:04:29,478
So in this block mesh, it's not clear where the player should go next.

106
00:04:30,058 --> 00:04:32,720
Sure, the ladder affords climbing up the little tower, but then what?

107
00:04:33,020 --> 00:04:34,521
Jump to the cliff? Dive in the water?

108
00:04:35,061 --> 00:04:36,201
What if we add some affordances?

109
00:04:37,020 --> 00:04:38,260
It becomes clear where to go.

110
00:04:38,960 --> 00:04:41,081
The boards on the roof afford jumping to the cliff,

111
00:04:42,701 --> 00:04:44,622
while the edge grabs on the cliffs afford climbing.

112
00:04:45,202 --> 00:04:47,603
Of course, this example is tailor-made for Uncharted,

113
00:04:48,123 --> 00:04:51,264
but the game's same concepts will apply to your traversal mechanics.

114
00:04:52,064 --> 00:04:53,905
It may seem silly to add them so early,

115
00:04:54,185 --> 00:04:57,405
but trust me, it makes a world of difference in how your playtests go,

116
00:04:57,606 --> 00:04:58,826
and it doesn't take that much effort.

117
00:05:00,045 --> 00:05:04,648
And one more thing, ensure these affordances use consistent shape and color.

118
00:05:05,208 --> 00:05:08,551
Follow the game metrics and you empower your team with this information.

119
00:05:09,191 --> 00:05:11,613
They could even be prefab objects that the whole team can use.

120
00:05:13,234 --> 00:05:15,095
Next tip, denying affordance.

121
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:20,159
While affordances are important at showing the player what they can interact with,

122
00:05:20,559 --> 00:05:23,000
showing them what they cannot interact with is also important.

123
00:05:23,701 --> 00:05:27,203
This is denying affordance and it prevents player frustration and guides them.

124
00:05:28,557 --> 00:05:31,539
Now you can't just disable a ladder or place an invisible wall.

125
00:05:31,839 --> 00:05:35,921
I mean, you can, but you shouldn't because it's frustrating to players.

126
00:05:37,081 --> 00:05:41,784
So you need to contextualize why you can't use the affordance by adding clearly visible

127
00:05:41,824 --> 00:05:44,045
things that say, can't use this or don't go there.

128
00:05:45,685 --> 00:05:49,107
Also make sure the reason for denied affordance is clear in your block mesh.

129
00:05:50,470 --> 00:05:53,772
At Naughty Dog, we record when a playtester tries to jump

130
00:05:54,293 --> 00:05:55,734
and grab something that they can't grab.

131
00:05:56,274 --> 00:05:58,455
We call these bad jumps and overlay them

132
00:05:58,515 --> 00:06:00,116
as red spheres in the game so that we

133
00:06:00,136 --> 00:06:01,497
can identify problem areas.

134
00:06:02,218 --> 00:06:04,179
Often, we'll find something that looks climbable

135
00:06:04,239 --> 00:06:05,260
but isn't supposed to be.

136
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:07,701
So we'll cover it with foliage or something.

137
00:06:07,781 --> 00:06:10,263
And after the next playtest, those bad jumps will be gone.

138
00:06:11,163 --> 00:06:12,444
Like sanding down a piece of wood,

139
00:06:12,784 --> 00:06:14,866
this process makes the levels play smoother.

140
00:06:16,735 --> 00:06:18,616
Here's an example of using spiky shapes

141
00:06:18,756 --> 00:06:20,457
and breaking up the horizontal edge

142
00:06:20,577 --> 00:06:21,758
to deny climbing affordance.

143
00:06:22,959 --> 00:06:25,200
Even though the window is within climbing range,

144
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:27,721
you still can't grab it because it's visually blocked.

145
00:06:28,622 --> 00:06:30,203
Notice how this is contextualized

146
00:06:30,423 --> 00:06:32,324
to the environment with bricks and rebar.

147
00:06:33,264 --> 00:06:35,726
This is important for games grounded in reality.

148
00:06:36,666 --> 00:06:39,187
For games not so grounded, you can get away with a lot,

149
00:06:39,388 --> 00:06:39,988
and that's OK.

150
00:06:40,948 --> 00:06:42,969
Just find the right tone and context for your world

151
00:06:43,009 --> 00:06:45,091
to make it feel natural and still deny affordance.

152
00:06:45,966 --> 00:06:46,947
Now let's see some block mesh.

153
00:06:47,908 --> 00:06:50,430
Let's say that we want the player to go through the window on the right,

154
00:06:50,710 --> 00:06:51,551
which is busted open.

155
00:06:52,832 --> 00:06:54,913
The left window is covered with a bush,

156
00:06:55,494 --> 00:06:58,737
and the front porch window and door are blocked with boards.

157
00:07:00,098 --> 00:07:01,579
Most players will glance at this house

158
00:07:01,659 --> 00:07:03,420
and go right for that window in a playtest.

159
00:07:03,801 --> 00:07:05,342
The intended way forward is open,

160
00:07:05,662 --> 00:07:08,024
while the rest of the entrance affordances are denied.

161
00:07:10,366 --> 00:07:11,968
Next tip, shape language.

162
00:07:13,310 --> 00:07:17,552
Establishing a consistent shape language communicates affordance and guides players.

163
00:07:18,973 --> 00:07:21,755
Climbing edges in Uncharted are always horizontal and flat.

164
00:07:22,355 --> 00:07:28,639
As a player, you learn this visual language of Ford's climbing and you can spot it easily.

165
00:07:29,920 --> 00:07:34,643
Also, people tend to have emotional associations with certain types of primitive shapes, which

166
00:07:34,703 --> 00:07:37,025
is even common across cultures.

167
00:07:38,266 --> 00:07:42,348
We can use this to our advantage to guide players toward or away from certain shapes.

168
00:07:43,344 --> 00:07:45,245
Round shapes tend to be viewed as non-threatening.

169
00:07:45,525 --> 00:07:46,726
There's nothing to stab you with.

170
00:07:47,907 --> 00:07:50,468
Rectangular shapes are viewed as stable and trustworthy,

171
00:07:51,349 --> 00:07:51,929
like a shelter.

172
00:07:52,950 --> 00:07:55,411
And diagonal shapes are viewed as aggressive and dangerous,

173
00:07:55,531 --> 00:07:56,111
like a spear.

174
00:07:57,792 --> 00:07:59,033
Now let's take a look at a screenshot

175
00:07:59,053 --> 00:08:01,515
from Uncharted, The Lost Legacy, and highlight the shapes.

176
00:08:03,416 --> 00:08:05,237
As you can see, the spiky shapes feel

177
00:08:05,257 --> 00:08:07,318
a little bit uncomfortable, possibly causing

178
00:08:07,358 --> 00:08:08,479
you to want to avoid those areas.

179
00:08:09,476 --> 00:08:12,097
The round areas aren't a threat and they actually provide stealth.

180
00:08:12,877 --> 00:08:16,338
And the square shapes are combat cover or buildings, nice and stable.

181
00:08:17,079 --> 00:08:19,139
All of this subtly guides the player to the buildings.

182
00:08:19,859 --> 00:08:21,300
Now let's see what it looks like in Block Mesh.

183
00:08:22,740 --> 00:08:24,601
Let's say we want the players to go to the right

184
00:08:25,061 --> 00:08:28,182
and they're being chased, so exploration will wreck pacing.

185
00:08:29,103 --> 00:08:32,044
The path sort of leads there, but some players may veer to the left.

186
00:08:32,264 --> 00:08:33,904
So how can we gently nudge them to the right?

187
00:08:35,585 --> 00:08:36,945
First let's add some spiky trees

188
00:08:37,225 --> 00:08:39,026
and some other pine trees that angle toward the goal.

189
00:08:40,176 --> 00:08:41,296
Then we'll add some round bushes.

190
00:08:43,157 --> 00:08:44,438
Finally, we'll add a small building.

191
00:08:44,718 --> 00:08:45,918
And I'm not going to lie, at this point,

192
00:08:45,958 --> 00:08:46,599
I kind of feel like this.

193
00:08:49,580 --> 00:08:50,340
But with a lot less hair.

194
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:54,061
All right, let's highlight those shapes we just added.

195
00:08:54,847 --> 00:08:57,328
The spiky shapes say danger, and they discourage going there.

196
00:08:58,249 --> 00:09:00,751
The square building implies, hey, stability is this way.

197
00:09:01,571 --> 00:09:03,392
The round stepping stones on the ground

198
00:09:03,553 --> 00:09:05,334
act as breadcrumbs to that stability,

199
00:09:05,934 --> 00:09:07,795
and the round bushes kind of act as bumpers

200
00:09:08,096 --> 00:09:09,116
to frame the play space.

201
00:09:09,757 --> 00:09:11,598
Of course, none of this prevents the player

202
00:09:11,618 --> 00:09:12,639
from going wherever they want.

203
00:09:13,279 --> 00:09:14,860
It just gently guides them where they should go.

204
00:09:16,581 --> 00:09:17,702
Next tip, color language.

205
00:09:19,758 --> 00:09:23,601
When you're trying to establish a consistent visual language in your affordances,

206
00:09:23,641 --> 00:09:24,482
shape is only half of it.

207
00:09:25,202 --> 00:09:26,884
You also need a consistent color as well.

208
00:09:28,585 --> 00:09:33,008
Adding color provides valuable context for an otherwise barren block mesh.

209
00:09:33,589 --> 00:09:35,510
It also adds depth if you're making a 3D game.

210
00:09:36,871 --> 00:09:39,373
Coloring also speeds up collaboration with your team

211
00:09:39,593 --> 00:09:42,235
because at a glance, they can get it without explanation.

212
00:09:43,236 --> 00:09:45,337
Is the ground supposed to be dirt, lava, water?

213
00:09:46,973 --> 00:09:51,296
Now Naughty Dog is notorious for using contrasting colors to draw the eye to where you should go.

214
00:09:52,396 --> 00:09:57,038
Here we have a bright yellow sign and rail, and it subtly lets the player know where to put the plank.

215
00:09:57,659 --> 00:10:03,081
Most people won't question why only one rail is yellow, they'll just remember that they intuitively knew where to go.

216
00:10:05,142 --> 00:10:06,743
Here we have white climbable edges.

217
00:10:07,783 --> 00:10:08,864
And here are some more edges.

218
00:10:09,304 --> 00:10:11,665
But wait, these are green. I thought you said to be consistent.

219
00:10:12,350 --> 00:10:14,492
Well, it's not a single color that's important.

220
00:10:14,852 --> 00:10:17,254
It's using consistent color and shapes

221
00:10:17,414 --> 00:10:18,916
in the context of the environment.

222
00:10:19,556 --> 00:10:21,037
Try to blend them into the environment

223
00:10:21,057 --> 00:10:23,519
so it looks natural but still stands out.

224
00:10:24,680 --> 00:10:26,421
Let's see how color can age a block mesh.

225
00:10:27,462 --> 00:10:28,503
Here we have a gray box.

226
00:10:29,424 --> 00:10:31,545
It's not really clear where the player should go

227
00:10:31,565 --> 00:10:32,826
or where they even can go.

228
00:10:33,527 --> 00:10:35,268
Affordances are gray and they're hard to see.

229
00:10:36,189 --> 00:10:37,530
Also, what kind of environment is this?

230
00:10:37,710 --> 00:10:39,131
A desert? An icy planet?

231
00:10:40,998 --> 00:10:42,598
First, let's add color to the affordances

232
00:10:42,778 --> 00:10:45,559
so that you can see them and the path forward, sort of.

233
00:10:46,539 --> 00:10:47,680
But we're still missing the context.

234
00:10:47,740 --> 00:10:48,560
What is this place?

235
00:10:48,780 --> 00:10:50,180
You know, everything blends together.

236
00:10:51,481 --> 00:10:51,721
Boom.

237
00:10:53,001 --> 00:10:54,582
We add color to the top of the blocks,

238
00:10:54,762 --> 00:10:56,702
and suddenly you're in a grassy, mountainous area

239
00:10:56,802 --> 00:10:57,683
with water down below.

240
00:10:58,383 --> 00:11:00,243
As you can see, adding color to your block mesh

241
00:11:00,303 --> 00:11:03,784
helps contextualize the level to the players and to teammates.

242
00:11:04,545 --> 00:11:06,705
And to further ground this on Earth, let's add some props.

243
00:11:09,316 --> 00:11:12,678
Now, color is important, but it shouldn't be the only thing that you rely on because

244
00:11:12,698 --> 00:11:13,958
some players are colorblind.

245
00:11:14,399 --> 00:11:19,281
You should combine color with other techniques, like unique shapes, and using contrasting

246
00:11:19,321 --> 00:11:20,862
color values rather than hues.

247
00:11:21,642 --> 00:11:25,724
Bonus points if you can get colorblind playtesters or teammates to help identify problems, and

248
00:11:25,764 --> 00:11:26,925
make your game more accessible.

249
00:11:28,265 --> 00:11:29,386
Next tip, landmarks.

250
00:11:39,266 --> 00:11:40,787
Here's the bridge. That's our way out of here.

251
00:11:42,729 --> 00:11:45,972
Ever wonder why game characters spend so much time pointing at things in the distance?

252
00:11:47,213 --> 00:11:50,335
Well, that's because they're landmarks, and they're a great way to orient players in your world.

253
00:11:51,476 --> 00:11:56,000
A landmark is basically just a big object that can be seen from far away and from different vantage points.

254
00:11:56,681 --> 00:11:59,944
If used correctly, players will see this object over and over as they get closer to it

255
00:12:00,164 --> 00:12:01,785
to let them know they're headed in the right direction.

256
00:12:03,145 --> 00:12:05,650
Landmarks also act as a goal for the player to work toward.

257
00:12:06,190 --> 00:12:07,232
They're also called weenies.

258
00:12:08,034 --> 00:12:09,416
If you want to know more about that,

259
00:12:09,516 --> 00:12:10,918
just Google Disney and weenies.

260
00:12:11,459 --> 00:12:12,401
Don't worry, it's safe for work.

261
00:12:13,302 --> 00:12:13,783
Probably.

262
00:12:15,185 --> 00:12:16,366
It depends if your safe search is on.

263
00:12:17,006 --> 00:12:17,947
All right, check this out.

264
00:12:18,627 --> 00:12:19,948
Zelda, the Breath of the Wild, really

265
00:12:19,988 --> 00:12:21,049
goes nuts with the landmarks.

266
00:12:21,469 --> 00:12:24,031
In just this one shot, there are several visible all in a row,

267
00:12:24,291 --> 00:12:25,632
and they're not overlapping one another.

268
00:12:26,072 --> 00:12:27,333
They also have unique silhouettes

269
00:12:27,513 --> 00:12:29,855
so you don't confuse them, which is also a great tip.

270
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:32,597
Try to have unique silhouettes for things in your game

271
00:12:32,817 --> 00:12:34,759
so that players can distinguish them at a glance.

272
00:12:34,779 --> 00:12:36,860
All right, block mesh time.

273
00:12:37,861 --> 00:12:39,602
Let's add a landmark to this block mesh.

274
00:12:41,747 --> 00:12:47,010
It's pretty basic, but it can have a huge impact on drawing the player toward a certain direction.

275
00:12:47,670 --> 00:12:52,152
If I'm working with a landmark, I like to add it first and then build the level backwards from there.

276
00:12:52,753 --> 00:12:55,574
That way I can always see it in the distance and shape the level accordingly.

277
00:12:56,714 --> 00:12:58,115
Next tip, openings attract.

278
00:12:59,236 --> 00:13:02,297
Caves, doors, etc. They all seem to attract people toward them.

279
00:13:03,438 --> 00:13:07,340
These openings often lead to a refuge space, which psychologically feels safe.

280
00:13:08,745 --> 00:13:12,148
Openings also have an air of mystery about them, and people want to see what's inside.

281
00:13:12,928 --> 00:13:17,092
This attraction happens in the real world with hobbies like spelunking and urban exploration.

282
00:13:18,713 --> 00:13:23,517
Here in Titanfall 2, a ramp affords jumping to a nicely lit opening that begs to be explored.

283
00:13:25,139 --> 00:13:28,221
This underwater opening lets you know that there's something beyond it if you swim for

284
00:13:28,281 --> 00:13:28,341
it.

285
00:13:30,343 --> 00:13:31,464
It even works in block worlds.

286
00:13:31,684 --> 00:13:33,125
As soon as I saw this, I went right for it.

287
00:13:35,027 --> 00:13:36,828
Doors and archways also draw you inside,

288
00:13:36,948 --> 00:13:38,690
even though an archway may not have a roof above it.

289
00:13:40,992 --> 00:13:42,673
When adding openings to block mesh,

290
00:13:42,933 --> 00:13:44,755
it's important to have different colors

291
00:13:44,795 --> 00:13:46,456
for interior and exterior walls.

292
00:13:47,337 --> 00:13:48,958
Here we have a cool white exterior

293
00:13:49,018 --> 00:13:50,139
and a warm yellow interior.

294
00:13:50,920 --> 00:13:52,781
This helps players read depth in your block mesh.

295
00:13:53,442 --> 00:13:54,923
If they're the same color, it's hard to tell

296
00:13:54,963 --> 00:13:56,104
that it's even an opening.

297
00:13:57,065 --> 00:13:59,727
Also, communicate this design intent to your artist

298
00:13:59,747 --> 00:14:01,609
to ensure that they know that this is an entrance

299
00:14:01,909 --> 00:14:02,970
and that it needs to stand out.

300
00:14:04,297 --> 00:14:07,018
Next tip, gates and valves.

301
00:14:08,599 --> 00:14:09,059
Terrible joke.

302
00:14:09,079 --> 00:14:12,380
All right, no, not those gates and valves, the kind that make way more money.

303
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:14,100
We want the level design kind.

304
00:14:15,200 --> 00:14:17,901
Gates stop progress until some sort of conditions are met.

305
00:14:18,421 --> 00:14:21,362
You've killed all the enemies, you've moved the debris out of the way, etc.

306
00:14:22,223 --> 00:14:23,083
Valves are the opposite.

307
00:14:23,603 --> 00:14:26,804
They let players move forward and then they slam the door shut behind them so they can't

308
00:14:26,824 --> 00:14:27,464
get backtrack.

309
00:14:28,865 --> 00:14:32,926
In this scenario, we want the player to enter the combat space and be trapped until combat's

310
00:14:33,006 --> 00:14:33,146
over.

311
00:14:33,994 --> 00:14:37,837
We have a valve into the space and then a gate at the other end blocking them so they can't leave.

312
00:14:39,058 --> 00:14:44,241
Once they enter, the gates and valves reduce the possibility space of the world to just the combat zone.

313
00:14:44,982 --> 00:14:48,604
Also, there's less mentally to keep track of so players can focus on the task at hand.

314
00:14:50,485 --> 00:14:56,229
It may look like this is only useful in linear games, but open world games can use it too with scenarios like arena battles.

315
00:14:56,770 --> 00:15:01,193
The Halo series did a great job of having big open levels that gated and valved players when needed.

316
00:15:03,137 --> 00:15:04,358
Now gates are pretty straightforward.

317
00:15:04,498 --> 00:15:06,339
There's something in your way, and you need to clear it.

318
00:15:06,839 --> 00:15:09,241
So I'll focus on valves, which can be a little more nuanced.

319
00:15:09,701 --> 00:15:11,462
In this valve example, you drop down,

320
00:15:11,542 --> 00:15:12,503
and you can't get back up.

321
00:15:29,573 --> 00:15:31,454
A fairly famous valve is in Super Metroid.

322
00:15:32,300 --> 00:15:34,282
where an entire chunk of level acts like a valve.

323
00:15:34,902 --> 00:15:37,865
At some point, the player falls down this really long shaft and there's no way back up.

324
00:15:39,206 --> 00:15:42,068
They're stuck, and the vast possibility space of the game is reduced

325
00:15:42,348 --> 00:15:43,990
to a tiny portion as seen on the map.

326
00:15:45,070 --> 00:15:46,932
In this space, they find two critical items,

327
00:15:47,252 --> 00:15:48,533
the high jump boots and the ice beam,

328
00:15:48,994 --> 00:15:51,696
and they learn to freeze enemies and then jump off of them

329
00:15:52,176 --> 00:15:53,937
so that they can use it to escape the shaft.

330
00:15:54,778 --> 00:15:58,221
The shaft that was once a valve has now become a gate that needs to be overcome.

331
00:15:59,405 --> 00:16:00,706
Given the entire world to explore,

332
00:16:00,746 --> 00:16:02,748
they may have never discovered this ability.

333
00:16:04,269 --> 00:16:05,570
Next tip, leading lines.

334
00:16:06,831 --> 00:16:08,553
Leading lines are a composition technique

335
00:16:08,873 --> 00:16:10,314
where lines in the environment draw the eye

336
00:16:10,354 --> 00:16:11,796
to a specific place in the scene.

337
00:16:12,716 --> 00:16:15,639
In this photo, the logs dry the eye up and into the frame

338
00:16:15,899 --> 00:16:17,020
to finally rest on the house.

339
00:16:18,301 --> 00:16:20,263
In games, these are often things like roads and pipes

340
00:16:20,303 --> 00:16:21,584
and cables and all sorts of stuff.

341
00:16:22,825 --> 00:16:25,407
Here in Titanfall 2, we wanted the player to focus on this door

342
00:16:25,487 --> 00:16:26,949
and not miss the reveal of a new enemy.

343
00:16:27,948 --> 00:16:30,089
Pipes and floor grates form leading lines to the door.

344
00:16:31,409 --> 00:16:33,350
And when you get close, a stalker rips the door open

345
00:16:33,390 --> 00:16:34,250
for a grand reveal.

346
00:16:36,231 --> 00:16:38,512
Here in the block mesh is a hallway with a T-junction

347
00:16:38,532 --> 00:16:38,952
at the end.

348
00:16:39,972 --> 00:16:41,873
Let's say you wanted the player to go to the right again.

349
00:16:42,673 --> 00:16:43,993
Right now, it's a coin toss.

350
00:16:44,554 --> 00:16:47,495
They may turn left, see a locked door and turn around,

351
00:16:47,875 --> 00:16:50,256
or they may smoothly go to the right and enter the next area.

352
00:16:51,436 --> 00:16:52,717
By adding some leading lines, though,

353
00:16:53,017 --> 00:16:54,357
we can draw their attention to the right

354
00:16:54,717 --> 00:16:56,078
and increase the chances they'll go there.

355
00:16:56,847 --> 00:17:00,108
Pipes on the walls and rug guide the player down the hallway.

356
00:17:01,229 --> 00:17:03,929
But the pipes on the left stop while the pipes on the right

357
00:17:03,969 --> 00:17:05,870
go along around the corner, drawing the eye.

358
00:17:07,130 --> 00:17:09,931
The caution cones break up the red line of the rug going left.

359
00:17:11,252 --> 00:17:14,533
And to go over the top, we add a big bright yellow cable

360
00:17:14,913 --> 00:17:17,274
that hugs the right side and goes along around the corner.

361
00:17:17,834 --> 00:17:20,195
Just some simple shapes, but it can have a huge impact

362
00:17:20,335 --> 00:17:22,175
on smooth navigation in your play tests.

363
00:17:23,396 --> 00:17:24,216
Next tip, pinching.

364
00:17:26,038 --> 00:17:28,839
Pinching basically means your layout funnels the player to a specific spot.

365
00:17:29,319 --> 00:17:34,742
You accomplish this by blocking off areas and angling shapes to naturally flow to that spot.

366
00:17:35,042 --> 00:17:37,223
It's good for redirecting players to a specific area,

367
00:17:37,783 --> 00:17:39,824
and it's also a great way to set up a cool reveal,

368
00:17:40,885 --> 00:17:43,486
like the view of a landmark, without forcing the camera to look at it.

369
00:17:44,106 --> 00:17:45,827
If you pinch them to a specific spot,

370
00:17:46,207 --> 00:17:48,708
the camera will be naturally pointed at the thing you want them to see.

371
00:17:53,843 --> 00:17:56,624
Of course, all of this completely depends on your mobility mechanics.

372
00:17:57,025 --> 00:17:59,886
It's much easier to do this in a game where players are stuck on the ground

373
00:18:00,146 --> 00:18:02,446
than in something like Titanfall where they're flying all over the place.

374
00:18:03,347 --> 00:18:04,307
Let's look at an example.

375
00:18:05,527 --> 00:18:07,948
Here, the buses and cars are angled to a specific spot,

376
00:18:08,789 --> 00:18:09,949
which you can see highlighted here.

377
00:18:11,369 --> 00:18:15,651
Walking down the street, the shapes naturally bring you to the end of the pinch,

378
00:18:16,071 --> 00:18:17,632
which faces the way forward.

379
00:18:19,205 --> 00:18:20,065
Let's see it in action.

380
00:18:20,665 --> 00:18:22,686
In this video, the pinch lines up a perfect shot

381
00:18:22,706 --> 00:18:24,647
of the hospital in the distance, which is your goal,

382
00:18:25,287 --> 00:18:26,367
and the tunnel that takes you there.

383
00:18:40,313 --> 00:18:41,773
Next tip, framing and composition.

384
00:18:43,450 --> 00:18:45,451
Another technique borrowed from photography.

385
00:18:45,931 --> 00:18:48,572
By framing your subject, be it a landmark, a big enemy,

386
00:18:48,652 --> 00:18:50,453
or a cave opening, you draw attention to it.

387
00:18:51,473 --> 00:18:52,374
If you'd like to learn more, just

388
00:18:52,394 --> 00:18:54,435
Google some photography composition techniques.

389
00:18:54,455 --> 00:18:55,295
You'll find lots of stuff.

390
00:18:57,176 --> 00:18:59,117
This one's really useful when combined with pinching

391
00:18:59,317 --> 00:19:00,898
to set up an important reveal on the level.

392
00:19:01,498 --> 00:19:03,499
After you pinch the player to a specific spot,

393
00:19:04,019 --> 00:19:06,840
perfectly frame the object for maximum effect.

394
00:19:07,520 --> 00:19:08,341
Let's see it in action.

395
00:19:17,717 --> 00:19:20,198
As you saw, the player is naturally pointed at the dam,

396
00:19:20,338 --> 00:19:22,799
and due to good framing, it was the dominant thing on screen.

397
00:19:23,499 --> 00:19:26,460
Also, a side tip, people's eyes are drawn to detail,

398
00:19:26,580 --> 00:19:27,861
and the dam is very detailed.

399
00:19:28,861 --> 00:19:30,202
All of this with just some layout

400
00:19:30,282 --> 00:19:31,342
and no forced camera moves.

401
00:19:33,003 --> 00:19:34,563
All right, next tip, breadcrumbs.

402
00:19:35,264 --> 00:19:35,924
Aw, yes.

403
00:19:38,065 --> 00:19:40,106
Breadcrumbs lead the player a little piece at a time

404
00:19:40,146 --> 00:19:40,606
to the goal.

405
00:19:41,706 --> 00:19:43,847
They can be almost anything, chunks of stuff on the ground,

406
00:19:43,987 --> 00:19:47,268
pickup items, enemies, lit areas, et cetera.

407
00:19:48,199 --> 00:19:50,680
It's usually better to add breadcrumbs to your block mesh

408
00:19:50,860 --> 00:19:52,680
after the early play tests, because they

409
00:19:52,700 --> 00:19:54,921
can hide fundamental layout guidance problems.

410
00:19:55,641 --> 00:19:57,502
But if you still need them after a few revisions,

411
00:19:57,542 --> 00:19:58,562
don't feel bad about adding them.

412
00:19:59,842 --> 00:20:02,003
In this example, the bits on the fence and roof

413
00:20:02,263 --> 00:20:04,424
create a visual stepping stones to the ledge.

414
00:20:06,024 --> 00:20:08,965
In Destiny 2, these panels guide the player into the tunnel.

415
00:20:10,686 --> 00:20:11,846
Now, if your game has pickups.

416
00:20:12,732 --> 00:20:14,773
They're a classic way to breadcrumb players around the level.

417
00:20:15,273 --> 00:20:17,173
Like how many times have you played a Mario game

418
00:20:17,353 --> 00:20:18,873
and the coins led you to a new area?

419
00:20:20,434 --> 00:20:22,914
Pickups are also great for letting players know they're on the right path

420
00:20:22,994 --> 00:20:24,554
in a cluttered or maze-like environment.

421
00:20:25,094 --> 00:20:27,455
This one's placed next to an area that you can duck under,

422
00:20:27,575 --> 00:20:29,315
which some players forget they can even do.

423
00:20:29,815 --> 00:20:31,916
So it subtly hints, yep, you're going the right way.

424
00:20:33,976 --> 00:20:34,976
So to go back to this house,

425
00:20:35,396 --> 00:20:38,397
let's say only half the players during our last playtest went into the house,

426
00:20:38,717 --> 00:20:39,817
and the other half got lost.

427
00:20:41,238 --> 00:20:44,001
Let's add some rocks and boards as breadcrumbs leading to the window.

428
00:20:44,562 --> 00:20:47,604
Notice how the boards are angled toward the window, creating leading lines.

429
00:20:48,645 --> 00:20:52,629
You can also sprinkle these breadcrumbs in open world areas to lead players to interesting

430
00:20:52,669 --> 00:20:54,811
things like the panels in the Destiny example.

431
00:20:56,393 --> 00:20:57,354
Next tip, textures.

432
00:20:58,454 --> 00:21:02,016
You can use textures to subtly or sometimes obviously point the way to a goal.

433
00:21:02,756 --> 00:21:07,059
These can be just about anything. Arrows, scrapes on the wall, signs, etc.

434
00:21:07,899 --> 00:21:13,222
Here in Uncharted, The Lost Legacy, scrape textures on the wall communicate a fordance that you can shimmy here.

435
00:21:14,002 --> 00:21:19,785
This example leads to a secret area and a collectible, so it's a good example that you don't need to do this for just the main path.

436
00:21:21,747 --> 00:21:22,307
Here in Uncharted 4...

437
00:21:23,757 --> 00:21:27,020
These tire tracks on the rock communicate affordance that you can drive here.

438
00:21:27,721 --> 00:21:30,543
Now, when I played this game, I didn't notice the tire tracks and I got lost.

439
00:21:31,604 --> 00:21:32,305
I didn't work on this game.

440
00:21:34,167 --> 00:21:34,867
I worked on the next one.

441
00:21:37,090 --> 00:21:40,112
Once I noticed the tire tracks, though, the rest of it driving went totally smoothly.

442
00:21:41,514 --> 00:21:44,336
Signs literally point the way to the hospital, which is also your goal.

443
00:21:45,457 --> 00:21:47,499
These textures are often some of the last things added

444
00:21:47,579 --> 00:21:48,399
when making a level.

445
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:50,761
So it seems like it's not really going

446
00:21:50,781 --> 00:21:51,822
to help your block mesh phase.

447
00:21:52,062 --> 00:21:52,622
But guess what?

448
00:21:53,323 --> 00:21:54,704
You don't need to wait for an artist to add them.

449
00:21:55,624 --> 00:21:56,405
You can cheat.

450
00:21:56,705 --> 00:21:59,567
And you can build them out of block mesh for your play tests.

451
00:22:00,368 --> 00:22:02,829
Here I've added an arrow and a sign to point the way.

452
00:22:03,830 --> 00:22:06,052
And these scratch marks lead into the alley,

453
00:22:06,152 --> 00:22:07,973
indicating something heavy was dragged back there.

454
00:22:08,713 --> 00:22:09,314
And the best part?

455
00:22:10,295 --> 00:22:11,215
These are all just block mesh.

456
00:22:12,579 --> 00:22:16,641
Labeling rooms and areas can be super helpful for both linear and open games.

457
00:22:17,381 --> 00:22:22,044
If you're building a school, for example, having labels like gym and cafeteria provide

458
00:22:22,084 --> 00:22:24,785
valuable context and signposts as your players explore.

459
00:22:30,736 --> 00:22:34,299
Here I've pulled this away from the wall a bit so you can see that it's just a bunch of blocks.

460
00:22:34,840 --> 00:22:38,343
This stuff only takes a couple minutes to do and it works wonders for your play tests

461
00:22:38,643 --> 00:22:41,406
and also to communicate with your artist where you think signage might go.

462
00:22:42,247 --> 00:22:45,530
And I'm not going to lie, this one is so easy and simple and obvious,

463
00:22:45,770 --> 00:22:47,051
it kind of blew my mind when I learned it.

464
00:22:47,071 --> 00:22:49,233
Alright, next tip.

465
00:22:50,194 --> 00:22:50,514
Movement.

466
00:22:51,175 --> 00:22:53,197
Movement grabs the eye and the player's attention.

467
00:22:54,392 --> 00:22:55,772
This can be anything that fits your game.

468
00:22:55,912 --> 00:22:59,154
Big scripted moments, birds, sparks, buddies, enemies,

469
00:22:59,414 --> 00:23:01,856
and even just something flapping in the breeze.

470
00:23:03,556 --> 00:23:05,698
Also, make good use of the direction of the movement.

471
00:23:06,078 --> 00:23:07,659
The player's eye will follow the movement

472
00:23:07,939 --> 00:23:09,580
and it can draw an invisible line

473
00:23:09,640 --> 00:23:10,740
right to where you want them to go.

474
00:23:10,760 --> 00:23:13,101
In this example I'm about to show,

475
00:23:13,402 --> 00:23:15,083
the birds draw your attention to the left

476
00:23:15,943 --> 00:23:17,364
where there's this open trailer door.

477
00:23:17,824 --> 00:23:19,645
And the trailer door is also banging in the wind.

478
00:23:19,905 --> 00:23:22,046
Both of these things kind of subtly let you know,

479
00:23:22,086 --> 00:23:23,707
like hey, maybe you should check out what's inside.

480
00:23:38,459 --> 00:23:39,740
And the dead body totally helps too.

481
00:23:41,361 --> 00:23:45,385
Of course, adding movement in the block mesh phase is highly dependent on your game and engine.

482
00:23:46,005 --> 00:23:48,047
If you can, though, try to include them in your playtests.

483
00:23:48,388 --> 00:23:50,730
Maybe not in the first ones, but definitely before you lock it down.

484
00:23:51,651 --> 00:23:52,631
And you don't have to get fancy.

485
00:23:52,711 --> 00:23:56,175
You can have basic cubes just lurping through the sky as a placeholder for birds.

486
00:23:57,636 --> 00:24:00,839
Now, adding movement is also super useful as a bandage late in development

487
00:24:01,319 --> 00:24:04,222
when the level is basically done, but players are still getting lost.

488
00:24:05,199 --> 00:24:08,120
Since the level itself is done, you can script in some movement to help.

489
00:24:08,641 --> 00:24:12,262
But don't rely on it though, like try to solve the player guidance problems in the

490
00:24:12,282 --> 00:24:12,942
block mesh phase.

491
00:24:14,103 --> 00:24:17,865
Last tip, light and god rays, aka light rays or sun beams.

