599
00:29:24,174 --> 00:29:27,095
So first let's start with a brief history of light.

600
00:29:29,877 --> 00:29:32,538
A very brief and simple history of light

601
00:29:32,578 --> 00:29:34,359
might start with the sun, right?

602
00:29:34,459 --> 00:29:35,560
The sun is really great.

603
00:29:35,580 --> 00:29:37,141
Let's give it up now for the sun.

604
00:29:37,941 --> 00:29:40,182
Although it's going to rain a lot, I'm told.

605
00:29:40,282 --> 00:29:42,744
So you won't see much sun in the next few days.

606
00:29:43,884 --> 00:29:49,289
There's also fire, controlled burning in gas lamps, incandescent light bulbs with filament

607
00:29:49,349 --> 00:29:50,730
and run current through the filament.

608
00:29:51,110 --> 00:29:56,174
There's also a stronger focus these days on energy efficient light sources like fluorescent

609
00:29:56,214 --> 00:29:59,257
lighting or LED lighting is also becoming more common.

610
00:30:00,298 --> 00:30:07,003
And I think it's very tempting to think of this as a story about technology and progress

611
00:30:07,203 --> 00:30:11,347
and older light sources becoming obsolete or something.

612
00:30:12,737 --> 00:30:15,340
That's not exactly true, and I don't think that's exactly accurate.

613
00:30:15,520 --> 00:30:20,005
Like, the light bulb did not make the sun obsolete, right?

614
00:30:20,065 --> 00:30:23,970
Like, you still like going outside and playing in the sun or whatever you do in the sun.

615
00:30:24,871 --> 00:30:26,273
I wouldn't know, I'm a game developer.

616
00:30:28,083 --> 00:30:32,126
The LED did not make the fire obsolete, right?

617
00:30:32,947 --> 00:30:38,571
You'll go to a restaurant, maybe tonight, and have a nice candlelit dinner or something,

618
00:30:39,211 --> 00:30:43,875
and the flickering candle, it's really nice when that's actual fire,

619
00:30:43,935 --> 00:30:46,777
not one of those weird LED flickering things, right?

620
00:30:49,668 --> 00:30:55,590
So as a society, I think we still use fire as a light source, not necessarily as like

621
00:30:55,630 --> 00:30:59,452
a task light source where you like write letters by candlelight or something.

622
00:31:00,052 --> 00:31:03,373
But you know, it's still in our birthday candles, our campfires.

623
00:31:04,173 --> 00:31:08,875
Fire hasn't disappeared, but our culture around fire has changed.

624
00:31:09,335 --> 00:31:12,996
Fire used to be common, and now it's kind of more like a special occasion kind of thing.

625
00:31:13,116 --> 00:31:15,417
But it's still here in civilization.

626
00:31:16,622 --> 00:31:19,644
So each of these light sources means something different

627
00:31:19,984 --> 00:31:21,305
and makes a space feel different.

628
00:31:21,865 --> 00:31:24,607
And I urge you to pay attention to the different moods

629
00:31:24,687 --> 00:31:26,848
and atmospheres these different light sources evoke.

630
00:31:29,870 --> 00:31:32,051
And today, contemporary lighting design

631
00:31:32,191 --> 00:31:36,473
has been kind of heavily standardized and industrialized.

632
00:31:37,374 --> 00:31:38,975
If you're a lighting designer and you're

633
00:31:39,015 --> 00:31:42,096
shopping for light fixtures or luminaires,

634
00:31:42,356 --> 00:31:43,157
as they're called in Europe,

635
00:31:43,837 --> 00:31:49,440
It's very common to, on the left right there, that's like a picture of like a lighting catalog.

636
00:31:50,180 --> 00:31:53,342
And the lighting catalog gives you all these different stats so you can kind of predict

637
00:31:53,422 --> 00:31:54,323
what the light will do.

638
00:31:55,143 --> 00:31:58,785
And there's also usually often like a chart in that lower left.

639
00:31:58,985 --> 00:32:00,966
I've blown up the chart on the right there.

640
00:32:02,506 --> 00:32:04,427
And that's a light distribution curve chart.

641
00:32:04,567 --> 00:32:10,750
And that kind of shows you how much light that light source or light fixture is going to throw at every given angle.

642
00:32:11,290 --> 00:32:14,631
So notice this light bulb with that light distribution chart on the right.

643
00:32:15,352 --> 00:32:19,133
It's kind of shaped like a heart a little bit and has like a crease at the top.

644
00:32:19,473 --> 00:32:23,315
Well, that makes sense, right, because the light socket is on top.

645
00:32:23,535 --> 00:32:26,076
It's not going to throw light through the light socket.

646
00:32:26,116 --> 00:32:26,936
That doesn't make sense.

647
00:32:26,956 --> 00:32:29,237
So it's mainly throwing light downwards and to the right.

648
00:32:29,317 --> 00:32:32,598
So now you know how to read a light distribution chart.

649
00:32:32,798 --> 00:32:33,379
It's pretty easy.

650
00:32:35,460 --> 00:32:39,281
So this is how real life lighting design quantifies

651
00:32:39,581 --> 00:32:41,762
and standardizes the physics of light.

652
00:32:42,342 --> 00:32:45,984
But in video games, light is often much messier than this.

653
00:32:46,944 --> 00:32:51,186
So now I want to talk a little bit about what is game lighting

654
00:32:51,606 --> 00:32:52,607
and what do we mean by that.

655
00:32:54,821 --> 00:33:01,803
Light is a complex phenomenon that's hopefully elegant with a unified theorem and all that.

656
00:33:04,384 --> 00:33:10,906
All these phenomena like reflections, occlusion, translucence, shadows, all those happen in

657
00:33:10,946 --> 00:33:13,606
real life for free, so to speak.

658
00:33:14,507 --> 00:33:19,111
But in video games, lighting is like a bunch of crap in a box.

659
00:33:19,211 --> 00:33:19,852
We don't...

660
00:33:20,292 --> 00:33:23,715
It's just a bunch of random systems that we, like, hack and tune together,

661
00:33:24,256 --> 00:33:28,600
and we throw all that crap in a video game and then pray it'll look okay in the end.

662
00:33:29,341 --> 00:33:31,763
So it's not a beautiful, elegant system.

663
00:33:32,123 --> 00:33:33,545
It's just a bunch of random stuff.

664
00:33:34,465 --> 00:33:39,168
And to give you an idea of all that random stuff, right, in any given game engine there's

665
00:33:39,448 --> 00:33:44,671
different cascading shadow maps, there's refraction shaders, there's caustics, there's fog, there's

666
00:33:44,731 --> 00:33:51,035
glow sprites, HDR, screen space ambient occlusion, bloom, all these different things are all

667
00:33:51,135 --> 00:33:53,376
kind of representing one system.

668
00:33:53,516 --> 00:33:56,758
But in a video game, it's like 20 different systems, right?

669
00:33:57,338 --> 00:34:01,280
And we kind of just turn them on and turn them off on like a case-by-case basis.

670
00:34:01,641 --> 00:34:08,387
So when you play a video game, maybe when you go in this room, that's when they turn on some screen space reflection.

671
00:34:08,708 --> 00:34:14,033
And then when you go in this other room, they turn off screen space reflection to save on framerate and optimize it and stuff.

672
00:34:14,994 --> 00:34:19,738
And again, from a physics perspective, that makes zero sense.

673
00:34:19,778 --> 00:34:24,723
The idea that you can turn off shadows in real life makes no sense.

674
00:34:26,527 --> 00:34:28,388
That would just be like, you should go see a doctor

675
00:34:28,428 --> 00:34:29,168
if that happens, right?

676
00:34:29,188 --> 00:34:29,828
That's not good.

677
00:34:31,128 --> 00:34:35,130
So again, video games, we rely on this piecemeal approach

678
00:34:35,170 --> 00:34:36,830
of all this random stuff together.

679
00:34:38,371 --> 00:34:40,491
So in this talk, I'm not going to be talking

680
00:34:40,811 --> 00:34:42,252
about a lot of those effects.

681
00:34:42,352 --> 00:34:44,852
I'm going to be focusing on what I view as the fundamentals

682
00:34:44,992 --> 00:34:48,193
of lighting in level design, which are basically

683
00:34:48,233 --> 00:34:51,414
these four basic light types, directional light, spotlight,

684
00:34:51,574 --> 00:34:52,955
ambient light, and point light.

685
00:34:56,020 --> 00:35:00,265
So let's say you're mocking up a level in Unity or something,

686
00:35:00,585 --> 00:35:02,828
and you don't have any lights going on.

687
00:35:02,908 --> 00:35:05,390
It's just a dark level, no lights there yet.

688
00:35:05,991 --> 00:35:07,513
And I just have a bunch of blocks there.

689
00:35:09,925 --> 00:35:12,247
So first you might add some ambient light.

690
00:35:12,568 --> 00:35:16,170
Ambient light is a kind of like default amount of light

691
00:35:16,210 --> 00:35:17,411
you might add to a scene.

692
00:35:17,612 --> 00:35:19,473
It refers to the whole scene.

693
00:35:19,533 --> 00:35:20,274
It's global.

694
00:35:20,954 --> 00:35:23,957
And you do that to make sure those shadows in your levels

695
00:35:24,097 --> 00:35:25,258
aren't pitch black.

696
00:35:25,738 --> 00:35:28,200
Because in real life, very few things

697
00:35:28,280 --> 00:35:30,862
are just pitch black like that, unless you're in a really

698
00:35:30,922 --> 00:35:32,063
dark cave or something.

699
00:35:32,283 --> 00:35:34,805
There's always a little bit of light bouncing around

700
00:35:34,886 --> 00:35:35,286
everywhere.

701
00:35:35,606 --> 00:35:37,428
So ambient light is kind of meant

702
00:35:37,468 --> 00:35:38,789
to simulate that a little bit.

703
00:35:39,703 --> 00:35:44,346
But notice when we add ambient light, that doesn't really help us read the shapes or anything.

704
00:35:44,627 --> 00:35:46,508
It's still very flat, right?

705
00:35:47,168 --> 00:35:52,151
You still can't really see the shapes that well, but you can just distinguish the silhouette.

706
00:35:54,013 --> 00:35:56,174
So that's when you might add another light source.

707
00:35:56,595 --> 00:35:58,535
So here's a directional light.

708
00:35:58,595 --> 00:36:00,796
Directional light is a global light source.

709
00:36:01,077 --> 00:36:04,118
It illuminates the entire scene at once from one given

710
00:36:04,158 --> 00:36:04,858
direction.

711
00:36:05,619 --> 00:36:07,519
And it usually doesn't matter where you position a

712
00:36:07,559 --> 00:36:09,840
directional light, depending on what tool you're using.

713
00:36:10,421 --> 00:36:12,662
And now with the directional light, you can read the shapes

714
00:36:12,842 --> 00:36:15,903
much more clearly, because you add that directionality

715
00:36:15,943 --> 00:36:16,903
component to it now.

716
00:36:17,404 --> 00:36:19,144
And notice how everything pops out more.

717
00:36:20,018 --> 00:36:24,059
In games we usually use directional light, usually for like sunlight or maybe moonlight

718
00:36:24,119 --> 00:36:24,539
or something.

719
00:36:26,580 --> 00:36:27,820
Then we also have a spotlight.

720
00:36:28,321 --> 00:36:31,482
If the scene is set at night, maybe you want to add some streetlights.

721
00:36:32,222 --> 00:36:34,302
For a streetlight you might want to use a spotlight.

722
00:36:34,322 --> 00:36:39,684
A spotlight throws a light in a cone shape in a given direction and from a given position.

723
00:36:39,764 --> 00:36:45,386
So here I'm using a spotlight as a downlight to emphasize this walkable floor area instead

724
00:36:45,446 --> 00:36:46,927
of emphasizing something else.

725
00:36:49,947 --> 00:36:52,389
And lastly, I want to talk about the point light.

726
00:36:52,549 --> 00:36:54,730
The point light throws light in every direction.

727
00:36:55,170 --> 00:36:58,031
Some tool sets might call this an omnidirectional light,

728
00:36:58,131 --> 00:37:00,252
or you can call it an omni light for short,

729
00:37:00,292 --> 00:37:02,133
which makes it sound really cool, omni light.

730
00:37:02,473 --> 00:37:07,256
But you imagine a point light as this invisible ball of light

731
00:37:07,556 --> 00:37:10,197
that's just washing everything nearby with light.

732
00:37:11,178 --> 00:37:12,919
So a point light, I think, is usually

733
00:37:12,939 --> 00:37:15,500
really good at drawing attention to a focal point,

734
00:37:15,520 --> 00:37:18,041
because it ends up creating kind of this hot spot

735
00:37:18,141 --> 00:37:19,002
effect a little bit.

736
00:37:20,903 --> 00:37:25,812
In contrast with a spotlight, it's not always clear where the spotlight is shining from,

737
00:37:25,832 --> 00:37:29,739
especially if it's a spotlight like a floodlight shooting light across.

738
00:37:32,242 --> 00:37:35,544
And in practice, you should try to use all four lighting types at once,

739
00:37:35,804 --> 00:37:38,085
because they all can work together really well.

740
00:37:38,465 --> 00:37:40,006
Ambient helps bring up the shadows.

741
00:37:40,307 --> 00:37:42,748
Directional light helps make those background buildings pop

742
00:37:43,148 --> 00:37:45,470
and helps guide the main mood of the scene.

743
00:37:45,870 --> 00:37:48,091
Then you also have a spotlight highlighting an area.

744
00:37:48,331 --> 00:37:50,513
Then you also have a point light highlighting the street light.

745
00:37:50,893 --> 00:37:53,915
And again, all this stuff works together, helps create depth.

746
00:37:54,855 --> 00:37:58,938
It helps push a background and a foreground for your scene.

747
00:37:59,578 --> 00:38:00,899
And that's good.

748
00:38:02,427 --> 00:38:09,448
And with these light sources, I would argue that they form like a complete domain of lighting

749
00:38:09,508 --> 00:38:09,888
tools.

750
00:38:11,069 --> 00:38:16,270
So stretching this gamut from like a global light source that affects everything to a

751
00:38:16,330 --> 00:38:20,671
local light source that only affects nearby things or a light source that shines in one

752
00:38:20,691 --> 00:38:25,492
direction or all directions, I feel like it's like a complete domain kind of.

753
00:38:26,792 --> 00:38:31,793
So again, that's why every 3D engine or tool set usually has these light sources.

754
00:38:35,629 --> 00:38:39,372
So now we should talk a little bit about how we should use

755
00:38:39,412 --> 00:38:40,192
these light sources.

756
00:38:40,993 --> 00:38:44,716
And I'm going to talk about a lighting theory called

757
00:38:44,756 --> 00:38:49,920
three-point lighting, which is a very common form of lighting

758
00:38:49,980 --> 00:38:53,583
design theory that's very common in film and photography.

759
00:38:53,663 --> 00:38:55,725
So if you have a background in that, this will seem very

760
00:38:55,785 --> 00:38:56,485
familiar to you.

761
00:38:58,417 --> 00:39:02,200
The basic idea of three-point lighting is that you have three different light types.

762
00:39:02,920 --> 00:39:07,003
And here's a diagram that hopefully explains some of it.

763
00:39:07,283 --> 00:39:12,287
In that top left we have a combined composite of three different light types, but we can

764
00:39:12,327 --> 00:39:15,790
also break down what each light is doing into a separate channel.

765
00:39:16,090 --> 00:39:19,012
So that's what those other three smaller pictures are doing.

766
00:39:19,812 --> 00:39:22,254
And in the top right, you have a key light.

767
00:39:22,534 --> 00:39:24,755
The key light is kind of like your brightest light source,

768
00:39:25,255 --> 00:39:28,677
and it kind of sets the dominant lighting angle and mood

769
00:39:28,737 --> 00:39:30,838
for your scene or picture or image.

770
00:39:31,439 --> 00:39:33,800
Then in the bottom left, we have a fill light.

771
00:39:34,240 --> 00:39:36,562
A fill light helps brighten up the shadows,

772
00:39:36,622 --> 00:39:38,863
kind of like the ambient light we were talking about before,

773
00:39:39,123 --> 00:39:41,484
and helps fill in the darker parts.

774
00:39:41,945 --> 00:39:43,966
Usually you want this at a lower intensity

775
00:39:44,006 --> 00:39:44,986
than your key light.

776
00:39:46,126 --> 00:39:49,169
Then in the lower right, we have the rim light.

777
00:39:49,950 --> 00:39:53,513
And it's also sometimes called a back light or a hair light,

778
00:39:53,573 --> 00:39:54,674
depending on what you're doing.

779
00:39:55,135 --> 00:39:56,877
And it illuminates your silhouette

780
00:39:56,917 --> 00:39:59,459
to help pop it out from the background very faintly.

781
00:39:59,519 --> 00:40:01,901
Otherwise, the hair might end up, or the top of the head

782
00:40:01,941 --> 00:40:03,623
might be blending in with the background.

783
00:40:03,663 --> 00:40:07,567
So notice they do some specular and stuff on top like that.

784
00:40:10,049 --> 00:40:12,630
And a very common three-point kind of setup

785
00:40:12,670 --> 00:40:14,631
might end up looking a little bit like this.

786
00:40:15,572 --> 00:40:17,292
You have a key light and fill light, usually kind

787
00:40:17,312 --> 00:40:18,913
of at opposing angles.

788
00:40:18,933 --> 00:40:20,514
You usually don't want them falling

789
00:40:20,554 --> 00:40:22,935
the same direction and position, because then that

790
00:40:22,955 --> 00:40:24,015
kind of defeats the purpose.

791
00:40:24,595 --> 00:40:27,377
So usually you want fill and key to be at least

792
00:40:27,437 --> 00:40:29,097
different angles and positions.

793
00:40:30,406 --> 00:40:35,371
And in film and photography, there's also often the background light, that optional

794
00:40:35,391 --> 00:40:35,972
light right there.

795
00:40:36,672 --> 00:40:41,217
The background light helps brighten the background to help get rid of any awkward shadows that

796
00:40:41,257 --> 00:40:42,539
come from the key and fill.

797
00:40:42,819 --> 00:40:45,902
Remember, in real life, they can't just turn off shadows for the key and fill.

798
00:40:46,182 --> 00:40:48,865
They actually have to have another light to get rid of that shadow.

799
00:40:52,969 --> 00:40:57,851
And if you basically watch any movie, you can kind of break down any given film shot

800
00:40:58,271 --> 00:41:02,293
along these lines and try to see what all the different light sources are doing.

801
00:41:02,733 --> 00:41:05,875
So these are some examples from a blog called Lighting Pixels.

802
00:41:06,475 --> 00:41:10,237
You can see there's a key light, a fill light, and a rim light on that left.

803
00:41:10,877 --> 00:41:14,519
The key light is kind of coming from that top left of that image.

804
00:41:15,279 --> 00:41:17,580
So then it kind of feels like sunlight, kind of.

805
00:41:18,461 --> 00:41:21,784
And everything in that image is kind of evenly illuminated, too.

806
00:41:21,864 --> 00:41:23,026
So it seems very readable.

807
00:41:23,706 --> 00:41:26,009
Meanwhile, on the right, the key light

808
00:41:26,149 --> 00:41:27,591
is not coming from the top.

809
00:41:27,631 --> 00:41:29,292
The key light's coming from below,

810
00:41:29,593 --> 00:41:31,595
which means it's probably not sunlight,

811
00:41:31,815 --> 00:41:33,777
unless these people are hanging upside down.

812
00:41:33,797 --> 00:41:35,079
That's probably not sunlight.

813
00:41:35,099 --> 00:41:35,159
So.

814
00:41:36,720 --> 00:41:41,444
To me, that means it's more like an artificial light source, maybe like a nice candle or something.

815
00:41:41,944 --> 00:41:49,909
And when that candle is illuminating from Bama's face, I feel like that sets up a very different mood in the right image versus the left image.

816
00:41:50,229 --> 00:41:56,594
The right image feels kind of more intimate and maybe even romantic. I don't know what movie that's from.

817
00:41:57,615 --> 00:41:59,318
Maybe they're breaking up or having a divorce.

818
00:41:59,438 --> 00:41:59,819
I don't know.

819
00:42:00,941 --> 00:42:03,004
Some shit is going down in that right image, right?

820
00:42:03,185 --> 00:42:05,669
But in the left image, zero shit, right?

821
00:42:05,729 --> 00:42:08,314
It's very, very nice and safe.

822
00:42:12,890 --> 00:42:18,571
And it's really important to note that with three-point lighting, it's referring to three

823
00:42:18,691 --> 00:42:20,212
types of light sources.

824
00:42:20,492 --> 00:42:23,313
You don't always need to place three lights in every scene.

825
00:42:23,753 --> 00:42:28,574
So for example, in that film shot on the left, there's only two light sources there, a key

826
00:42:28,594 --> 00:42:29,274
light and a rim.

827
00:42:29,294 --> 00:42:30,114
There's no fill.

828
00:42:30,394 --> 00:42:33,695
And the right side of his face is left in shadow.

829
00:42:33,975 --> 00:42:37,296
And that's OK if that's what you want to do with your lighting, and that's the mood you

830
00:42:37,316 --> 00:42:37,876
want to create.

831
00:42:38,737 --> 00:42:43,061
Same thing in that right image, there's only one light source, just one key to help kind

832
00:42:43,101 --> 00:42:46,444
of emphasize I think the extreme close-up and intimacy of that shot.

833
00:42:48,126 --> 00:42:52,811
So again, it's just about what you want to do with your lights and what you want your

834
00:42:52,851 --> 00:42:53,451
lights to say.

835
00:42:55,918 --> 00:42:57,820
So here's another example on main unity.

836
00:42:58,040 --> 00:43:01,303
Say you want to like light this hunky dude with three point light theory.

837
00:43:02,164 --> 00:43:06,529
The way I lit him, I had a key light kind of grazing him a little bit so I could like

838
00:43:06,569 --> 00:43:07,970
catch some muscle definition.

839
00:43:08,811 --> 00:43:14,537
And I had the fill light kind of a little off angle from there because I still wanted

840
00:43:14,557 --> 00:43:17,580
to maintain the key but I wanted to soften how the shadows were hitting him.

841
00:43:18,341 --> 00:43:23,044
If you see in the right, that's a variant without the fill light.

842
00:43:23,084 --> 00:43:27,208
And without the fill light, I felt like his face was too much in shadow and I couldn't

843
00:43:27,248 --> 00:43:28,288
read what was going on.

844
00:43:29,049 --> 00:43:34,513
And if you're like a beginner level designer, I would say most beginners forget to do the

845
00:43:34,613 --> 00:43:39,517
fill part, and if you're starting out, you should err on the side of more fill than less

846
00:43:39,658 --> 00:43:39,898
fill.

847
00:43:41,854 --> 00:43:46,939
And then lastly, I have a rim light, also kind of picking out the right side of his

848
00:43:46,999 --> 00:43:50,883
face there and help separating that from the background so you can read his features better.

849
00:43:52,796 --> 00:43:58,340
And as for implementation, here I'm actually using three directional lights in Unity, but

850
00:43:58,360 --> 00:44:03,544
just with the layer mask set to just one layer just for that object.

851
00:44:03,624 --> 00:44:07,227
So it ends up being not that expensive if you use the culling masks.

852
00:44:08,247 --> 00:44:11,950
In Unreal, you can use a feature called light channels, which kind of does the same thing.

853
00:44:11,970 --> 00:44:15,192
It's super useful for isolating light sources for objects.

854
00:44:15,933 --> 00:44:21,637
But most games end up doing just maybe one light source technically, with the key light

855
00:44:21,657 --> 00:44:26,901
might be your main directional light, but your fill might be ambient or spherical harmonics

856
00:44:26,961 --> 00:44:31,845
probes, and then your rim light might be Fresnel and reflection and stuff in your shader.

857
00:44:35,181 --> 00:44:38,723
But I think there's one big problem with three-point light

858
00:44:38,783 --> 00:44:41,604
theory for games, especially in regards to level design.

859
00:44:42,244 --> 00:44:46,706
And that is the fact that film and photography have a very

860
00:44:46,806 --> 00:44:48,907
tightly controlled camera perspective.

861
00:44:49,367 --> 00:44:51,548
But in video games, we often give camera

862
00:44:51,568 --> 00:44:52,689
control to the player.

863
00:44:53,469 --> 00:44:56,250
So if you were looking at this hunky dude,

864
00:44:56,290 --> 00:44:58,631
and then you walk around and admire

865
00:44:58,651 --> 00:45:01,592
the back of this hunky dude, now the key light

866
00:45:01,792 --> 00:45:03,993
isn't a key light anymore, because the viewing angle

867
00:45:04,013 --> 00:45:04,574
has changed.

868
00:45:04,874 --> 00:45:06,634
Now my rim light is like a key light.

869
00:45:06,915 --> 00:45:09,716
Now my fill light isn't visible or something.

870
00:45:09,736 --> 00:45:11,857
I don't even know what's going on in that image anymore.

871
00:45:12,557 --> 00:45:17,059
So one big problem here is that we can't really

872
00:45:17,299 --> 00:45:20,600
know where the player is going to see this object, which

873
00:45:20,640 --> 00:45:22,421
will affect how we compose our lighting.

874
00:45:24,362 --> 00:45:28,947
This is why a lot of 3D games, I think, end up vomiting rim shaders and Fresnel effects

875
00:45:29,067 --> 00:45:33,091
everywhere because they can't predict where the player's going to be looking at this object,

876
00:45:33,172 --> 00:45:39,458
so they just spam Fresnel and rim everywhere so that there's always some rim action going

877
00:45:39,618 --> 00:45:39,698
on.

878
00:45:39,839 --> 00:45:42,581
But, you know, that should be your last resort.

879
00:45:42,622 --> 00:45:44,283
Let's try to be more subtle than that.

880
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:50,822
And I would argue the way you can be more subtle is to think about how your level layout

881
00:45:51,002 --> 00:45:56,885
will facilitate the viewing angles for your subjects and then you can light accordingly

882
00:45:56,945 --> 00:45:58,566
and use that as a framing device.

883
00:45:59,206 --> 00:46:02,428
So your level layout is a lighting tool.

884
00:46:03,308 --> 00:46:09,332
You can suggest a view or frame a certain composition just by having the player move

885
00:46:09,372 --> 00:46:11,793
through a hallway and that will suggest an angle for them.

886
00:46:13,373 --> 00:46:18,595
That's also why you need to do a little bit of block out and block meshing before you

887
00:46:18,635 --> 00:46:22,116
do some lighting so that you have an idea of where the player is going to be going.

888
00:46:25,596 --> 00:46:32,078
And lastly I want to end with this section, how to light a level, and I want to walk you

889
00:46:32,138 --> 00:46:36,579
through some steps that I would recommend you take with your own levels if you're starting

890
00:46:36,659 --> 00:46:36,759
out.

891
00:46:38,400 --> 00:46:41,540
This example will be in Unreal, but you can do it in any engine basically.

892
00:46:42,810 --> 00:46:48,435
So first, you do your blockout or gray box or whatever you want to call it with just

893
00:46:48,455 --> 00:46:49,797
some basic real-time light.

894
00:46:50,177 --> 00:46:53,921
If you're doing some light baking, you don't want to do it at this stage because your level

895
00:46:53,981 --> 00:46:55,042
is constantly changing.

896
00:46:55,062 --> 00:46:59,126
You don't want to waste your time spending an hour lighting a room and then you end up

897
00:46:59,166 --> 00:47:00,567
deleting that room or something.

898
00:47:00,587 --> 00:47:01,668
Then you've wasted your time.

899
00:47:02,209 --> 00:47:06,272
So right here is when I recommend you just use some basic real-time light and not worry

900
00:47:06,312 --> 00:47:07,413
about the lighting so much.

901
00:47:08,134 --> 00:47:14,100
For Unreal, I like switching it, using stationary lights for this, and I also like enabling

902
00:47:14,140 --> 00:47:19,325
a setting called force no pre-computed lighting, which will help you not worry about light

903
00:47:19,385 --> 00:47:21,567
mapping and light map baking and stuff.

904
00:47:22,167 --> 00:47:24,688
And that's in the world settings in the Unreal Editor.

905
00:47:25,128 --> 00:47:27,249
And in Unity, I like using real-time lights,

906
00:47:27,649 --> 00:47:31,111
and I disable the auto-generate lighting checkbox

907
00:47:31,451 --> 00:47:34,532
so that you're not constantly sitting and waiting and stopping

908
00:47:34,932 --> 00:47:36,653
for the light maps to bake.

909
00:47:38,113 --> 00:47:40,554
Although I hear the light map's faster now or something.

910
00:47:40,574 --> 00:47:40,994
I don't know.

911
00:47:44,056 --> 00:47:44,476
Step two.

912
00:47:45,442 --> 00:47:48,867
Now you want to set up your main mood, your big mood in your scene.

913
00:47:49,628 --> 00:47:52,852
And to do that you want to set up your global lights.

914
00:47:52,972 --> 00:47:57,558
So remember ambient and directional, those apply to your whole entire game world.

915
00:47:57,598 --> 00:48:01,482
So now's maybe the time to set that up before you worry about smaller stuff.

916
00:48:02,907 --> 00:48:07,329
And here you can see I have a bunch of sunlight flooding in from those middle windows right

917
00:48:07,369 --> 00:48:07,549
here.

918
00:48:08,369 --> 00:48:15,073
And I want to set up the main mood of this level with like a big sunny sun-filled area.

919
00:48:15,753 --> 00:48:22,296
And to do that I need to set up the indirect light bounces, especially for directional

920
00:48:22,316 --> 00:48:23,017
light or sunlight.

921
00:48:23,657 --> 00:48:27,419
If you want something to feel like sunlight, you should be paying attention to your indirect

922
00:48:27,459 --> 00:48:28,259
light bounce settings.

923
00:48:29,260 --> 00:48:33,087
In Unity, that would be going to your light settings, and in Unreal, that would involve

924
00:48:33,107 --> 00:48:37,396
going to your world settings and adjust the lightmass section of the world settings, and

925
00:48:37,496 --> 00:48:40,563
also look at the skylight actor in your Unreal scene.

926
00:48:42,104 --> 00:48:46,867
And if you're not working with global illumination or light map baking for whatever reason, then

927
00:48:46,907 --> 00:48:51,710
the next best thing is to hand place invisible, faint point lights everywhere.

928
00:48:53,051 --> 00:48:58,675
If you're working on a game like, I hear there's a rumor that Fallout 4 did not have global

929
00:48:58,695 --> 00:49:05,979
illumination so they had to place faint point lights to simulate and fake all the sunlight

930
00:49:06,040 --> 00:49:06,920
bouncing everywhere.

931
00:49:07,661 --> 00:49:09,001
So you can totally do that as well.

932
00:49:11,095 --> 00:49:14,798
In Unity, I like switching those lights to not important so that they don't contribute

933
00:49:14,818 --> 00:49:15,658
to specular stuff.

934
00:49:16,139 --> 00:49:20,061
And in Unreal, I like increasing the minimum roughness on those lights so that they don't

935
00:49:20,622 --> 00:49:22,063
create hot spots in your reflections.

936
00:49:25,478 --> 00:49:29,962
Then step three, after you've kind of set up the main mood of your scene, now you should

937
00:49:30,002 --> 00:49:33,225
start thinking about the gameplay and lighting for your critical path.

938
00:49:34,005 --> 00:49:38,529
To review, the critical path is kind of like the ideal things that your ideal player would

939
00:49:38,569 --> 00:49:41,672
kind of do in a certain order or whatever in your level.

940
00:49:43,015 --> 00:49:47,437
And at this stage, you should probably focus on navigation and wayfinding.

941
00:49:48,077 --> 00:49:52,839
Does the player know various entrances and exits and know where they are?

942
00:49:53,299 --> 00:49:57,520
David talked about this a lot in his talk, about how they care a lot about wayfinding.

943
00:49:57,820 --> 00:49:59,561
Lighting is another tool for you to do that.

944
00:49:59,941 --> 00:50:06,083
And here, I'm using it in a really painfully obvious way, where I'm using bright orange

945
00:50:06,283 --> 00:50:08,224
lights on bright red doors.

946
00:50:09,984 --> 00:50:16,211
Feel free to be more subtle than that in your own work, but for the purposes of this example,

947
00:50:16,532 --> 00:50:17,713
it's super obvious.

948
00:50:19,512 --> 00:50:25,994
And when you're doing that, I also urge you to think about kind of like the hierarchy of different things you're doing here.

949
00:50:26,554 --> 00:50:32,416
Here, I would argue the left door is being lit to be more important than the door on the right.

950
00:50:32,696 --> 00:50:38,637
The door on the left kind of has a wider spotlight and it's more intense and brighter and also kind of has its own room and shadow.

951
00:50:38,657 --> 00:50:40,398
So the contrast is much stronger.

952
00:50:40,798 --> 00:50:48,580
Meanwhile, that door on the right, it's certainly an option and it certainly reads as like an entrance or exit to this room, but it's also a bit more faint.

953
00:50:48,680 --> 00:50:48,860
So.

954
00:50:49,261 --> 00:50:52,204
Now we're emphasizing this door on the left, super important.

955
00:50:52,404 --> 00:50:54,747
This door on the right, it's like okay.

956
00:50:55,047 --> 00:50:58,151
You know, it's an okay door, but you know, that door on the left, yeah.

957
00:51:01,217 --> 00:51:06,919
Then once you're done doing main player wayfinding, and also you're like testing throughout all of this, right,

958
00:51:07,779 --> 00:51:11,360
you should be thinking about the other interactions in your game.

959
00:51:11,720 --> 00:51:15,221
So if you're setting up any NPCs or set pieces or encounters,

960
00:51:15,542 --> 00:51:20,103
you should be trying to light those encounters so that the player will actually notice what's going on.

961
00:51:21,064 --> 00:51:25,926
So here, these are like critical gameplay objects that you might want to like, like

962
00:51:26,026 --> 00:51:31,068
enemies coming into the room, or maybe the enemies are like guarding an objective or

963
00:51:31,108 --> 00:51:31,648
something.

964
00:51:31,928 --> 00:51:34,129
So on the left, they're guarding this orb.

