00:51:34,409 --> 00:51:36,891
The orb is very important in this game, I assure you.

966
00:51:37,431 --> 00:51:43,554
And I have, I've set up a blue, blue-green kind of turquoise light, and it's kind of

967
00:51:43,594 --> 00:51:48,376
coming at this perpendicular angle to that orange arrow, which is what I imagine as the

968
00:51:48,416 --> 00:51:49,716
player's critical path in this.

969
00:51:50,437 --> 00:51:55,580
And when you have that blue light coming like a grazing perpendicular angle kind of,

970
00:51:55,920 --> 00:52:02,525
that helps set that up as a rim light to help emphasize the shapes going on there instead of the surfaces.

971
00:52:03,698 --> 00:52:05,819
Kind of the same thing going on in the example on the right.

972
00:52:06,020 --> 00:52:09,601
You might see two small people, two small silhouettes

973
00:52:09,681 --> 00:52:10,442
in the background.

974
00:52:11,102 --> 00:52:13,823
And that's because I've kind of thrown a background

975
00:52:13,883 --> 00:52:14,864
light behind them.

976
00:52:15,424 --> 00:52:17,865
So those silhouettes end up popping out,

977
00:52:17,985 --> 00:52:19,726
and you notice them really easily.

978
00:52:20,166 --> 00:52:21,807
So again, if you're lighting stuff

979
00:52:21,847 --> 00:52:24,829
where soldiers or enemies jump through windows or something,

980
00:52:25,049 --> 00:52:26,569
you might want to have a light behind them

981
00:52:26,589 --> 00:52:28,590
to help frame them and help them pop out.

982
00:52:32,910 --> 00:52:36,234
And when you're doing this, you should be thinking about your texture pass.

983
00:52:37,896 --> 00:52:40,239
Texturing is pretty important.

984
00:52:40,620 --> 00:52:44,665
I think that's why David talks about using color a lot. You should be thinking about the basic values.

985
00:52:45,546 --> 00:52:48,690
This is a page, I basically just took

986
00:52:48,730 --> 00:52:51,293
these from some Unreal UDK documentation.

