00:52:52,834 --> 00:52:57,716
Here the albedo on the left is really dark, and the albedo diffuse texture on the right is much brighter.

988
00:52:58,256 --> 00:53:02,217
And when you have that dark albedo, the light doesn't bounce as much,

989
00:53:02,398 --> 00:53:07,439
because most game engines use the albedo texture to calculate reflectance for indirect light.

990
00:53:07,960 --> 00:53:11,541
So you can see that scene ends up feeling really, really dark in a weird way.

991
00:53:11,941 --> 00:53:15,122
But if you use a brighter albedo, in that bottom right example,

992
00:53:15,443 --> 00:53:19,164
now the scene is kind of evenly illuminated and it feels much more like sunlight.

993
00:53:19,764 --> 00:53:24,126
And one really easy way to check this is if you open up your Albedo or Diffuse Texture in Photoshop,

994
00:53:24,446 --> 00:53:29,708
open up the Levels Histogram, look at that, most of your values should be more in the upper mid-range.

995
00:53:30,088 --> 00:53:34,489
And you usually want to leave the left and right, the extreme values, empty,

996
00:53:34,789 --> 00:53:39,071
so that lighting can do its work. So don't try to do extreme black or extreme white.

